# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: depth-of-field-rendering
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] In photography, **bokeh** (/ˈboʊkə/ *BOH-kə* or /ˈboʊkeɪ/ *BOH-kay*; Japanese: [boke]) is the aesthetic quality of the blur produced in out-of-focus parts of an image, whether foreground or background or both.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] It is created by using a wide aperture lens.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] Some photographers incorrectly restrict use of the term bokeh to the appearance of bright spots in the out-of-focus area caused by circles of confusion.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] Bokeh has also been defined as "the way the lens renders out-of-focus points of light".
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] Differences in lens aberrations and aperture shape cause very different bokeh effects.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] Some lens designs blur the image in a way that is pleasing to the eye, while others produce distracting or unpleasant blurring ("good" and "bad" bokeh, respectively).
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] Photographers may deliberately use a shallow focus technique to create images with prominent out-of-focus regions, accentuating their lens's bokeh.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] Bokeh is often most visible around small background highlights, such as specular reflections and light sources, which is why it is often associated with such areas.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] However, bokeh is not limited to highlights; blur occurs in all regions of an image which are outside the depth of field.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] The opposite of bokeh—an image in which multiple distances are visible and all are in focus—is deep focus.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] The term comes from the Japanese word *boke* (暈け/ボケ), which means "blur" or "haze", resulting in *boke-aji* (ボケ味), the "blur quality".
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] This is derived as a noun form of the verb *bokeru*, which is written in several ways, with additional meanings and nuances: 暈ける refers to being blurry, hazy or out-of-focus, whereas the 惚ける and 呆ける spellings refer to being mentally hazy, befuddled, childish, senile, or playing stupid.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] *Jisaboke* (時差ボケ) (literally, "time difference fog") is the term for jet lag.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] *Nebokeru* (寝ぼける) is a verb denoting the actions or condition of someone who is half-asleep, or nodding off.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] *Tobokeru* means playing dumb, and *toboketa kao* refers to a poker face.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] The related term *bokashi* (暈かし) means intentional blurring or gradation; that is a noun form of the transitive verb *bokasu* (暈す), which means to make something blurry, rather than to be blurry.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] The spellings *bokeh* and *boke* have both been in use since at least 1996, when Merklinger had suggested "or Bokeh if you prefer." The term *bokeh* has appeared in photography books as early as 1998.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] It is sometimes pronounced /ˈboʊkə/ *BOH-kə*.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] Though difficult to quantify, some lenses have subjectively more pleasing out-of-focus areas.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] "Good" bokeh is especially important for macro lenses and long telephoto lenses, because they are typically used in situations that produce shallow depth of field.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] Good bokeh is also important for medium telephoto lenses (typically 85–150 mm on 35 mm format).
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] When used in portrait photography (for their "natural" perspective), the photographer usually wants a shallow depth of field, so that the subject stands out sharply against a blurred background.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] Bokeh characteristics may be quantified by examining the image's circle of confusion.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] In out-of-focus areas, each point of light becomes an image of the aperture, generally a more or less round disc.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] Depending on how a lens is corrected for spherical aberration, the disc may be uniformly illuminated, brighter near the edge, or brighter near the center.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] A well-known lens that exhibited the latter "soap-bubble" characteristic was that produced by Hugo Meyer & Co., more recently revived by Meyer Optik Görlitz.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] Lenses that are poorly corrected for spherical aberration will show one kind of disc for out-of-focus points in front of the plane of focus, and a different kind for points behind.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] This may actually be desirable, as blur circles that are dimmer near the edges produce less-defined shapes which blend smoothly with the surrounding image.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] The shape of the aperture has an influence on the subjective quality of bokeh as well.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] For conventional lens designs (with bladed apertures), when a lens is stopped down smaller than its maximum aperture size (minimum f-number), out-of-focus points are blurred into the polygonal shape formed by the aperture blades.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] This is most apparent when a lens produces hard-edged bokeh.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] For this reason, some lenses have many aperture blades and/or blades with curved edges to make the aperture more closely approximate a circle rather than a polygon.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] Minolta has been on the forefront of promoting and introducing lenses with near-ideal circular apertures since 1987, but most other manufacturers now offer lenses with shape-optimized diaphragms, at least for the domain of portraiture photography.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] In contrast, a catadioptric telephoto lens renders bokehs resembling doughnuts, because its secondary mirror blocks the central part of the aperture opening.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] Recently, photographers have exploited the shape of the bokeh by creating a simple mask out of card with shapes such as hearts or stars, that the photographer wishes the bokeh to be, and placing it over the lens.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] Lenses with 11, 12, or 15 blade iris diaphragms are often claimed to excel in bokeh quality.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] Because of this, the lenses do not need to reach wide apertures to get better circles (instead of polygons).
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] In the past, wide aperture lenses (f/2, f/2.8) were very expensive, due to the complex mathematical design and manufacturing know-how required, at a time when all computations and glass making were done by hand.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] Leica could reach a good bokeh at f/4.5.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] Today it is much easier to make an f/1.8 lens, and a 9-bladed lens at f/1.8 is enough for an 85 mm lens to achieve great bokeh.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] Some lens manufacturers including Nikon, Minolta, and Sony make lenses designed with specific controls to change the rendering of the out-of-focus areas.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] The Nikon 105 mm DC-Nikkor and 135 mm DC-Nikkor lenses (DC stands for "Defocus Control") have a control ring that permits the overcorrection or undercorrection of spherical aberration to change the bokeh in front of and behind the focal plane.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] The Minolta/Sony STF 135 mm f/2.8 [T4.5] (with STF standing for *smooth trans focus*) is a lens specifically designed to produce pleasing bokeh.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] It is possible to choose between two diaphragms: one with 9 and another with 10 blades.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] An apodization filter is used to soften the aperture edges which results in a smooth defocused area with gradually fading circles.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] Those qualities made it the only lens of this kind on the market from its introduction in 1999 to 2014.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] In 2014 Fujifilm announced a lens utilizing a similar apodization filter in the Fujinon XF 56mm F1.2 R APD lens.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] Sony added the Sony FE 100 mm F2.8 STF GM OSS in 2017.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] The 'Sigma YS System Focusing' 135 mm f/2.8 also has an extra manually-moved component, intended to compensate for aberration at close-focus distances.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] It can be re-purposed for defocus control.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] In 2015, Meyer Optik USA Inc. launched a Kickstarter campaign to produce the Trioplan f2.9/50, a new lens based on one originally produced by Hugo Meyer & Co.; both lenses exhibit a characteristic "soap-bubble" bokeh.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] The use of anamorphic lenses will cause bokeh to appear differently along the horizontal and vertical axes of the lens, becoming ellipsoidal compared to those in a spherical lens.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] In 2016, Apple Inc. released the iPhone 7 Plus which can take pictures with "Portrait Mode" (a bokeh like effect).
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] Samsung's Galaxy Note 8 has a similar effect available.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] Both of these phones use dual cameras to detect edges and create a "depth map" of the image, which the phone uses to blur the out-of-focus portions of the photo.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] Other phones, like the Google Pixel, only use a single camera and machine learning to create the depth map.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] In 2017, Vivo released a smartphone with dual front lenses for selfies with bokeh.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] The first, a 20 MP lens, uses a 1/2.78" sensor with f/2.0 aperture, while the second, an 8 MP f/2.0 lens, captures depth information.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] Bokeh can be made with a combination of both lenses, and shots can be refocused even after they are captured, adding bokeh effects with different depths.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] In early 2018, the Honor 9 Lite smartphone was released with quad cameras (two dual-lens).
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] Both the front and back cameras have a 13 MP main lens and a 2 MP lens for capturing bokeh depth information.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] Bokeh can be simulated by convolving the image with a kernel that corresponds to the image of an out-of-focus point source taken with a real camera.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] Unlike conventional convolution, this convolution has a kernel that depends on the distance of each image point and – at least in principle – has to include image points that are occluded by objects in the foreground.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] To a first approximation, defocus blur is convolution by a uniform disk, a more computationally intensive operation than the "standard" Gaussian blur; the former produces sharp circles around highlights whereas the latter is a much softer effect.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] Diffraction may alter the effective shape of the blur.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] Some graphics editors have a filter to do this, usually called "Lens Blur".
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] Accurate bokeh simulation requires running the blur in linear, HDR space.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] For low dynamic range images, an artificial neural network may be used to reconstruct the HDR light.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] An alternative mechanical mechanism has been proposed for generating bokeh in small aperture cameras such as compacts or cellphone cameras, called image destabilisation, in which both the lens and sensor are moved in order to maintain focus at one focal plane, while defocusing nearby ones.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] This effect currently generates blur in only one axis.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] Some advanced digital cameras have bokeh features which take several images with different apertures and focuses and then manually compose them afterward to one image.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] More advanced systems of bokeh use a hardware system of 2 sensors, one sensor to take photo as usual while other ones record depth information.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] Bokeh effect and refocusing can then be applied to an image after the photo is taken.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] In 2009, a research group at MIT Media Lab showed that the bokeh effect can be used to make imperceptibly small barcodes, or bokodes.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/bokeh] By using barcodes as small as 3 mm with a small lens over them, if the barcode is viewed out of focus through an ordinary camera focused at infinity, the resulting image is large enough to scan the information in the barcode.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] In optics, a **circle of confusion** (CoC) is an optical spot caused by a cone of light rays from a lens not coming to a perfect focus when imaging a point source.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] It is also known as **disk of confusion**, **circle of indistinctness**, **blur circle**, or **blur spot**.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] In photography, the circle of confusion is used to determine the depth of field, the part of an image that is acceptably sharp.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] A standard value of CoC is often associated with each image format, but the most appropriate value depends on visual acuity, viewing conditions, and the amount of enlargement.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] Usages in context include *maximum permissible circle of confusion*, *circle of confusion diameter limit*, and the *circle of confusion criterion*.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] Real lenses do not focus all rays perfectly, so that even at best focus, a point is imaged as a spot rather than a point.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] The smallest such spot that a lens can produce is often referred to as the **circle of least confusion**.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] For describing the blur spot achieved by a lens, at its best focus or more generally.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] The term *circle of confusion* is applied more generally, to the size of the out-of-focus spot to which a lens images an object point.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] Diffraction effects from wave optics and the finite aperture of a lens determine the circle of least confusion; the more general usage of 'circle of confusion' for out-of-focus points can be computed purely in terms of ray (geometric) optics.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] In idealized ray optics, where rays are assumed to converge to a point when perfectly focused, the shape of a defocus blur spot from a lens with a circular aperture is a hard-edged circle of light.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] A more general blur spot has soft edges due to diffraction and aberrations, and may be non-circular due to the aperture shape.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] Therefore, the diameter concept needs to be carefully defined in order to be meaningful.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] Suitable definitions often use the concept of encircled energy, the fraction of the total optical energy of the spot that is within the specified diameter.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] Values of the fraction (e.g., 80%, 90%) vary with application.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] In photography, the circle of confusion diameter limit (*CoC limit* or *CoC criterion*) is often defined as the largest blur spot that will still be perceived by the human eye as a point, when viewed on a final image from a standard viewing distance.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] The CoC limit can be specified on a final image (e.g. a print) or on the original image (on film or image sensor).
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] If the final image is viewed at approximately 25 cm, a final-image CoC of 0.2 mm often is appropriate.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] But if the larger final image will be viewed at the normal distance of 25 cm, a smaller original-image CoC will be needed to provide acceptable sharpness.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] Enlargement from the original image to the final image.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] If there is no enlargement (e.g., a contact print of an 8×10 original image), the CoC for the original image is the same as that in the final image.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] But if, for example, the long dimension of a 35 mm (1.4 inches) original image is enlarged to 25 cm (10 inches), the enlargement factor is approximately 7, and the CoC for the original image is 0.2 mm / 7, or 0.029 mm.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] The common values for CoC limit may not be applicable if reproduction or viewing conditions differ significantly from those assumed in determining those values.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] If the original image will be given greater enlargement, or viewed at a closer distance, then a smaller CoC will be required.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] Since the final-image size is not usually known at the time of taking a photograph, it is common to assume a standard size such as 25 cm width, along with a conventional final-image CoC of 0.2 mm, which is 1/1250 of the image width.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] Conventions in terms of the diagonal measure are also commonly used.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] The DoF computed using these conventions will need to be adjusted if the original image is cropped before enlarging to the final image size, or if the size and viewing assumptions are altered.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] For full-frame 35 mm format (24 mm × 36 mm, 43 mm diagonal), a widely used CoC limit is d/1500, or 0.029 mm for full-frame 35 mm format, which corresponds to resolving 5 lines per millimeter on a print of 30 cm diagonal.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] Values of 0.030 mm and 0.033 mm are also common for full-frame 35 mm format.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] Criteria relating CoC to the lens focal length have also been used.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] Kodak recommended 2 minutes of arc (the Snellen criterion of 30 cycles/degree for normal vision) for critical viewing, yielding a CoC of about f/1720, where f is the lens focal length.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] For a 50 mm lens on full-frame 35 mm format, the corresponding CoC is 0.0291 mm.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] However, images seldom are viewed at the so-called 'correct' distance; the viewer usually does not know the focal length of the taking lens, and the "correct" distance may be uncomfortably short or long.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] Consequently, criteria based on lens focal length have generally given way to criteria (such as d/1500) related to the camera format.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] If an image is viewed on a low-resolution display medium such as a computer monitor, the detectability of blur will be limited by the display medium rather than by human vision.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] For example, the optical blur will be more difficult to detect in an 8 in × 10 in image displayed on a computer monitor than in an 8×10 print of the same original image viewed at the same distance.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] If the image is to be viewed only on a low-resolution device, a larger CoC may be appropriate; however, if the image may also be viewed in a high-resolution medium such as a print, the criteria discussed above will govern.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] Depth of field formulas derived from geometrical optics imply that any arbitrary DoF can be achieved by using a sufficiently small CoC.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] Because of diffraction, however, this is not quite true.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] Using a smaller CoC requires increasing the lens f-number to achieve the same DoF, and if the lens is stopped down sufficiently far, the reduction in defocus blur is offset by the increased blur from diffraction.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] See the Depth of field article for a more detailed discussion.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] The f-number determined from a lens DoF scale can be adjusted to reflect a CoC different from the one on which the DoF scale is based.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] where N is the lens f-number, c is the CoC, m is the magnification, and f is the lens focal length.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] Because the f-number and CoC occur only as the product Nc, an increase in one is equivalent to a corresponding decrease in the other.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] The same approach can usually be used with a DoF calculator on a view camera.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] The blur circle, of diameter C, in the focused object plane at distance *S*1, is an unfocused virtual image of the object at distance *S*2 as shown in the diagram.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] This formula is exact for a simple paraxial thin lens or a symmetrical lens, in which the entrance pupil and exit pupil are both of diameter A.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] More complex lens designs with a non-unity pupil magnification will need a more complex analysis, as addressed in depth of field.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] If either the focus distance or the out-of-focus subject distance is infinite, the equations can be evaluated in the limit.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] If the c value is fixed as a circle of confusion diameter limit, either of these can be solved for subject distance to get the hyperfocal distance, with approximately equivalent results.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] Before it was applied to photography, the concept of circle of confusion was applied to optical instruments such as telescopes.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] 54) quantifies both a *circle of least confusion* and a *least circle of confusion* for a spherical reflecting surface.
