[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] This latter statement is clearly incorrect, or misstated, being off by a factor of focal distance (focal length).
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] Numerically, 1/100 inch at 12–15 inches is closer to two minutes of arc.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] This choice of CoC limit remains (for a large print) the most widely used even today.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] 207–08) takes a similar approach based on a visual acuity of one minute of arc, and chooses a circle of confusion of 0.025 cm for viewing at 40–50 cm, essentially making the same factor-of-two error in metric units.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] It is unclear whether Abney or Dallmeyer was earlier to set the CoC standard thereby.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/circle-of-confusion] The common 1/100 inch CoC limit has been applied to blur other than defocus blur.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] The **depth of field** (**DOF**) is the distance between the nearest and the farthest objects that are in acceptably sharp focus in an image captured with a camera.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] See also the closely related **depth of focus**.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] This photo was taken with an aperture of f/22, creating a mostly in-focus background.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] The same scene as above with an aperture of f/1.8.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Notice how much blurrier the background appears in this photo.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] For cameras that can only focus on one object distance at a time, depth of field is the distance between the nearest and the farthest objects that are in acceptably sharp focus in the image.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] "Acceptably sharp focus" is defined using a property called the "circle of confusion".
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] The depth of field can be determined by focal length, distance to subject (object to be imaged), the acceptable circle of confusion size, and aperture.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] for a given maximum acceptable circle of confusion diameter c, focal length f, f-number N, and distance to subject u.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] As distance or the size of the acceptable circle of confusion increases, the depth of field increases; however, increasing the size of the aperture (i.e., reducing f-number) or increasing the focal length reduces the depth of field.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Depth of field changes linearly with f-number and circle of confusion, but changes in proportion to the square of the distance to the subject and inversely in proportion to the square of the focal length.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] As a result, photos taken at extremely close range (i.e., so small u) have a proportionally much smaller depth of field.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Note that ${\textstyle M_{T}=-{\frac {f}{u-f}}}$ is the transverse magnification which is the ratio of the lateral image size to the lateral subject size.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Image sensor size affects DOF in counterintuitive ways.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Because the circle of confusion is directly tied to the sensor size, decreasing the size of the sensor while holding focal length and aperture constant will *decrease* the depth of field (by the crop factor).
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] The resulting image will also have a different field of view.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] If, however, the focal length is altered to maintain the original field of view, while holding the aperture constant, the DOF will remain constant.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] For a given subject framing and camera position, the DOF is controlled by the lens aperture diameter, which is usually specified as the f-number (the ratio of lens focal length to aperture diameter).
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Reducing the aperture diameter (increasing the f-number) increases the DOF because only the light travelling at shallower angles passes through the aperture so only cones of rays with shallower angles reach the image plane.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] In other words, the circles of confusion are reduced or increasing the DOF.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] For a given size of the subject's image in the focal plane, the same f-number on any focal length lens will give the same depth of field.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] This is evident from the above DOF equation by noting that the ratio *u*/*f* is constant for constant image size.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] For example, if the focal length is doubled, the subject distance is also doubled to keep the subject image size the same.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] This observation contrasts with the common notion that "focal length is twice as important to defocus as f/stop", which applies to a constant subject distance, as opposed to constant image size.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Aperture settings are adjusted more frequently in still photography, where variations in depth of field are used to produce a variety of special effects.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] mm objective lens and full-frame DSLR camera.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Focus point is on the first blocks column.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Precise focus is only possible at an exact distance from a lens; at that distance, a point object will produce a small spot image.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Otherwise, a point object will produce a larger or blur spot image that is typically and approximately a circle.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] When this circular spot is sufficiently small, it is visually indistinguishable from a point, and appears to be in focus.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] The diameter of the largest circle that is indistinguishable from a point is known as the acceptable circle of confusion, or informally, simply as the circle of confusion.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] The acceptable circle of confusion depends on how the final image will be used.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] The circle of confusion as 0.25 mm for an image viewed from 25 cm away is generally accepted.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] For 35 mm motion pictures, the image area on the film is roughly 22 mm by 16 mm.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] The limit of tolerable error was traditionally set at 0.05 mm (0.0020 in) diameter, while for 16 mm film, where the size is about half as large, the tolerance is stricter, 0.025 mm (0.00098 in).
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] More modern practice for 35 mm productions set the circle of confusion limit at 0.025 mm (0.00098 in).
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] The term "camera movements" refers to swivel (swing and tilt, in modern terminology) and shift adjustments of the lens holder and the film holder.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] These features have been in use since the 1800s and are still in use today on view cameras, technical cameras, cameras with tilt/shift or perspective control lenses, etc.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Swiveling the lens or sensor causes the plane of focus (POF) to swivel, and also causes the field of acceptable focus to swivel with the POF; and depending on the DOF criteria, to also change the shape of the field of acceptable focus.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] While calculations for DOF of cameras with swivel set to zero have been discussed, formulated, and documented since before the 1940s, documenting calculations for cameras with non-zero swivel seem to have begun in 1990.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] More so than in the case of the zero swivel camera, there are various methods to form criteria and set up calculations for DOF when swivel is non-zero.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] There is a gradual reduction of clarity in objects as they move away from the POF, and at some virtual flat or curved surface the reduced clarity becomes unacceptable.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Some photographers do calculations or use tables, some use markings on their equipment, some judge by previewing the image.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] When the POF is rotated, the near and far limits of DOF may be thought of as wedge-shaped, with the apex of the wedge nearest the camera; or they may be thought of as parallel to the POF.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Traditional depth-of-field formulas can be hard to use in practice.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] As an alternative, the same effective calculation can be done without regard to the focal length and f-number.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Moritz von Rohr and later Merklinger observe that the effective absolute aperture diameter can be used for similar formula in certain circumstances.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Moreover, traditional depth-of-field formulas assume equal acceptable circles of confusion for near and far objects.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Merklinger suggested that distant objects often need to be much sharper to be clearly recognizable, whereas closer objects, being larger on the film, do not need to be so sharp.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] The loss of detail in distant objects may be particularly noticeable with extreme enlargements.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Achieving this additional sharpness in distant objects usually requires focusing beyond the hyperfocal distance, sometimes almost at infinity.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] For example, if photographing a cityscape with a traffic bollard in the foreground, this approach, termed the *object field method* by Merklinger, would recommend focusing very close to infinity, and stopping down to make the bollard sharp enough.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] With this approach, foreground objects cannot always be made perfectly sharp, but the loss of sharpness in near objects may be acceptable if recognizability of distant objects is paramount.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Other authors such as Ansel Adams have taken the opposite position, maintaining that slight unsharpness in foreground objects is usually more disturbing than slight unsharpness in distant parts of a scene.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Some methods and equipment allow altering the apparent DOF, and some even allow the DOF to be determined after the image is made.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] These are based or supported by computational imaging processes.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] For example, focus stacking combines multiple images focused on different planes, resulting in an image with a greater (or less, if so desired) apparent depth of field than any of the individual source images.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Similarly, in order to reconstruct the 3-dimensional shape of an object, a depth map can be generated from multiple photographs with different depths of field.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] The focal plane is swept across the entire relevant range during a single exposure.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] This creates a blurred image, but with a convolution kernel that is nearly independent of object depth, so that the blur is almost entirely removed after computational deconvolution.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] This has the added benefit of dramatically reducing motion blur.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Light Scanning Photomacrography (LSP) is another technique used to overcome depth of field limitations in macro and micro photography.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] This method allows for high-magnification imaging with exceptional depth of field.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] LSP involves scanning a thin light plane across the subject that is mounted on a moving stage perpendicular to the light plane.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] This ensures the entire subject remains in sharp focus from the nearest to the farthest details, providing comprehensive depth of field in a single image.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Initially developed in the 1960s and further refined in the 1980s and 1990s, LSP was particularly valuable in scientific and biomedical photography before digital focus stacking became prevalent.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Other technologies use a combination of lens design and post-processing: Wavefront coding is a method by which controlled aberrations are added to the optical system so that the focus and depth of field can be improved later in the process.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] The lens design can be changed even more: in colour apodization the lens is modified such that each colour channel has a different lens aperture.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] For example, the red channel may be f/2.4, green may be f/2.4, whilst the blue channel may be f/5.6.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Therefore, the blue channel will have a greater depth of field than the other colours.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] The image processing identifies blurred regions in the red and green channels and in these regions copies the sharper edge data from the blue channel.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] The result is an image that combines the best features from the different f-numbers.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] At the extreme, a plenoptic camera captures 4D light field information about a scene, so the focus and depth of field can be altered after the photo is taken.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Diffraction causes images to lose sharpness at high f-numbers (i.e., narrow aperture stop opening sizes), and hence limits the potential depth of field.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] However, diffraction is a greater issue in close-up photography, and the overall image sharpness can be degraded as photographers are trying to maximize depth of field with very small apertures.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Hansma and Peterson have discussed determining the combined effects of defocus and diffraction using a root-square combination of the individual blur spots.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Hansma's approach determines the f-number that will give the maximum possible sharpness; Peterson's approach determines the minimum f-number that will give the desired sharpness in the final image and yields a maximum depth of field for which the desired sharpness can be achieved.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] In combination, the two methods can be regarded as giving a maximum and minimum f-number for a given situation, with the photographer free to choose any value within the range, as conditions (e.g., potential motion blur) permit.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Gibson gives a similar discussion, additionally considering blurring effects of camera lens aberrations, enlarging lens diffraction and aberrations, the negative emulsion, and the printing paper.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Couzin gave a formula essentially the same as Hansma's for optimal f-number, but did not discuss its derivation.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Hopkins, Stokseth, and Williams and Becklund have discussed the combined effects using the modulation transfer function.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Many lenses include scales that indicate the DOF for a given focus distance and f-number; the 35 mm lens in the image is typical.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] That lens includes distance scales in feet and meters; when a marked distance is set opposite the large white index mark, the focus is set to that distance.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] The DOF scale below the distance scales includes markings on either side of the index that correspond to f-numbers.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] When the lens is set to a given f-number, the DOF extends between the distances that align with the f-number markings.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Photographers can use the lens scales to work backwards from the desired depth of field to find the necessary focus distance and aperture.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] For the 35 mm lens shown, if it were desired for the DOF to extend from 1 m to 2 m, focus would be set so that index mark was centered between the marks for those distances, and the aperture would be set to f/11.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] On a view camera, the focus and f-number can be obtained by measuring the depth of field and performing simple calculations.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Some view cameras include DOF calculators that indicate focus and f-number without the need for any calculations by the photographer.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] In optics and photography, hyperfocal distance is a distance from a lens beyond which all objects can be brought into an "acceptable" focus.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] As the hyperfocal distance is the focus distance giving the maximum depth of field, it is the most desirable distance to set the focus of a fixed-focus camera.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] The hyperfocal distance is entirely dependent upon what level of sharpness is considered to be acceptable.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Thomas Sutton and George Dawson first wrote about hyperfocal distance (or "focal range") in 1867.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Louis Derr in 1906 may have been the first to derive a formula for hyperfocal distance.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Rudolf Kingslake wrote in 1951 about the two methods of measuring hyperfocal distance.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Some cameras have their hyperfocal distance marked on the focus dial.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] For example, on the Minox LX focusing dial there is a red dot between 2 m and infinity; when the lens is set at the red dot, that is, focused at the hyperfocal distance, the depth of field stretches from 2 m to infinity.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Some lenses have markings indicating the hyperfocal range for specific f-stops, also called a *depth-of-field scale*.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] The DOF beyond the subject is always greater than the DOF in front of the subject.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] When the subject is at the hyperfocal distance or beyond, the far DOF is infinite, so the ratio is 1:∞; as the subject distance decreases, near:far DOF ratio increases, approaching unity at high magnification.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] For large apertures at typical portrait distances, the ratio is still close to 1:1.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] This section covers some additional formulas for evaluating depth of field; however they are all subject to significant simplifying assumptions: for example, they assume the paraxial approximation of Gaussian optics.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] They are suitable for practical photography, lens designers would use significantly more complex ones.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] the harmonic mean of the near and far distances.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] In practice, this is equivalent to the arithmetic mean for shallow depths of field.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] Sometimes, view camera users refer to the difference *v*N − *v*F as the *focus spread*.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] The minus sign applies to a foreground object, and the plus sign applies to a background object.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/depth-of-field] The blur increases with the distance from the subject; when b is less than the circle of confusion, the detail is within the depth of field.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] In photography, **exposure** is the amount of light per unit area reaching a frame of photographic film or the surface of an electronic image sensor.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] It is determined by exposure time, lens f-number, and scene luminance.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] Exposure is measured in units of lux-seconds (symbol lx⋅s), and can be computed from exposure value (EV) and scene luminance in a specified region.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] An "exposure" is a single shutter cycle.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] For example, a long exposure refers to a single, long shutter cycle to gather enough dim light, whereas a multiple exposure involves a series of shutter cycles, effectively layering a series of photographs in one image.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] The accumulated *photometric exposure* (*H*v) is the same so long as the total exposure time is the same.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] Only in this appropriately weighted case does the H measure the effective amount of light falling on the film, such that the characteristic curve will be correct independent of the spectrum of the light.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] Many photographic materials are also sensitive to "invisible" light, which can be a nuisance , or a benefit .
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] The use of radiometric units is appropriate to characterize such sensitivity to invisible light.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] In sensitometric data, such as characteristic curves, the *log exposure* is conventionally expressed as log10(*H*).
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] Photographers more familiar with base-2 logarithmic scales (such as exposure values) can convert using log2(*H*) ≈ 3.32 log10(*H*).
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] So-called "correct" exposure may be defined as an exposure that achieves the effect the photographer intended.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] A more technical approach recognises that a photographic film (or sensor) has a physically limited useful exposure range, sometimes called its dynamic range.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] If, for any part of the photograph, the actual exposure is outside this range, the film cannot record it accurately.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] In a very simple model, for example, out-of-range values would be recorded as "black" (underexposed) or "white" (overexposed) rather than the precisely graduated shades of colour and tone required to describe "detail".
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] Therefore, the purpose of exposure adjustment (and/or lighting adjustment) is to control the physical amount of light from the subject that is allowed to fall on the film, so that 'significant' areas of shadow and highlight detail do not exceed the film's useful exposure range.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] This ensures that no 'significant' information is lost during capture.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] The photographer may carefully overexpose or underexpose the photograph to *eliminate* what they judge as insignificant or unwanted detail; to make, for example, a white altar cloth appear immaculately clean, or to emulate the heavy, pitiless shadows of film noir.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] However, it is technically much easier to discard recorded information during post processing than to try to 're-create' unrecorded information.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] In a scene with strong or harsh lighting, the *ratio* between highlight and shadow luminance values may well be larger than the ratio between the film's maximum and minimum useful exposure values.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] A photograph may be described as *overexposed* when it has a loss of highlight detail, that is, when important bright parts of an image are "washed out" or effectively all white, known as "blown-out highlights" or "clipped whites".
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] A photograph may be described as *underexposed* when it has a loss of shadow detail, that is, when important dark areas are "muddy" or indistinguishable from black, known as "blocked-up shadows" (or sometimes "crushed shadows", "crushed blacks", or "clipped blacks", especially in video).
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] As the adjacent image shows, these terms are technical ones rather than artistic judgments; an overexposed or underexposed image may be "correct" in the sense that it provides the effect that the photographer intended.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] Intentionally over- or underexposing (relative to a standard or the camera's automatic exposure) is casually referred to as "exposing to the right" or "exposing to the left" respectively, as these shift the histogram of the image to the right or left.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] In manual mode, the photographer adjusts the lens aperture and/or shutter speed to achieve the desired exposure.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] Many photographers choose to control aperture and shutter independently because opening up the aperture increases exposure, but also decreases the depth of field, and a slower shutter increases exposure but also increases the opportunity for motion blur.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] "Manual" exposure calculations may be based on some method of light metering with a working knowledge of exposure values, the APEX system and/or the Zone System.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] A camera in **automatic exposure** or **autoexposure** (usually initialized as **AE**) mode automatically calculates and adjusts exposure settings to match (as closely as possible) the subject's mid-tone to the mid-tone of the photograph.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] For most cameras, this means using an on-board TTL exposure meter.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] Aperture priority (commonly abbreviated as *A*, or *Av* for "aperture value") mode gives the photographer manual control of the aperture, whilst the camera automatically adjusts the shutter speed to achieve the exposure specified by the TTL meter.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] Shutter priority (often abbreviated as *S*, or *Tv* for "time value") mode gives manual shutter control, with automatic aperture compensation.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] In each case, the actual exposure level is still determined by the camera's exposure meter.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] The purpose of an exposure meter is to estimate the subject's mid-tone luminance and indicate the camera exposure settings required to record this as a mid-tone.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] In order to do this it has to make a number of assumptions which, under certain circumstances, will be wrong.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] If the exposure setting indicated by an exposure meter is taken as the "reference" exposure, the photographer may wish to deliberately *overexpose* or *underexpose* in order to compensate for known or anticipated metering inaccuracies.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] Cameras with any kind of internal exposure meter usually feature an exposure compensation setting which is intended to allow the photographer to simply offset the exposure level from the internal meter's estimate of appropriate exposure.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] Frequently calibrated in stops, also known as EV units, a "+1" exposure compensation setting indicates one stop more (twice as much) exposure and "−1" means one stop less (half as much) exposure.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] Exposure compensation is particularly useful in combination with auto-exposure mode, as it allows the photographer to *bias* the exposure level without resorting to full manual exposure and losing the flexibility of auto exposure.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] On low-end video camcorders, exposure compensation may be the only manual exposure control available.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] An appropriate exposure for a photograph is determined by the sensitivity of the medium used.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] For photographic film, sensitivity is referred to as film speed and is measured on a scale published by the International Organization for Standardization (ISO).
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] Faster film, that is, film with a higher ISO rating, requires less exposure to make a readable image.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] Digital cameras usually have variable ISO settings that provide additional flexibility.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] Exposure is a combination of the length of time and the illuminance at the photosensitive material.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] Exposure time is controlled in a camera by shutter speed, and the illuminance depends on the lens aperture and the scene luminance.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] Slower shutter speeds (exposing the medium for a longer period of time), greater lens apertures (admitting more light), and higher-luminance scenes produce greater exposures.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] An approximately correct exposure will be obtained on a sunny day using ISO 100 film, an aperture of f/16 and a shutter speed of 1⁄100 of a second.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] This is called the sunny 16 rule: at an aperture of f/16 on a sunny day, a suitable shutter speed will be one over the film speed (or closest equivalent).
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] A scene can be exposed in many ways, depending on the desired effect a photographer wishes to convey.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] An important principle of exposure is reciprocity.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] If one exposes the film or sensor for a longer period, a reciprocally smaller aperture is required to reduce the amount of light hitting the film to obtain the same exposure.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] For example, the photographer may prefer to make their sunny-16 shot at an aperture of f/5.6 (to obtain a shallow depth of field).
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] As f/5.6 is 3 **stops** "faster" than f/16, with each stop meaning double the amount of light, a new shutter speed of (1⁄125)/(2·2·2) = 1⁄1000 s is needed.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] Once the photographer has determined the exposure, aperture stops can be traded for halvings or doublings of speed, within limits.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] The true characteristic of most photographic emulsions is not actually linear (see sensitometry), but it is close enough over the exposure range of about 1 second to 1⁄1000 of a second.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] Outside of this range, it becomes necessary to increase the exposure from the calculated value to account for this characteristic of the emulsion.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] This characteristic is known as *reciprocity failure*.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] The film manufacturer's data sheets should be consulted to arrive at the correction required, as different emulsions have different characteristics.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] Digital camera image sensors can also be subject to a form of reciprocity failure.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] The Zone System is another method of determining exposure and development combinations to achieve a greater tonality range over conventional methods by varying the contrast of the film to fit the print contrast capability.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] Digital cameras can achieve similar results (high dynamic range) by combining several different exposures (varying shutter or diaphragm) made in quick succession.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] Today, most cameras automatically determine the correct exposure at the time of taking a photograph by using a built-in light meter, or multiple point meters interpreted by a built-in computer, see metering mode.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] Negative and print film tends to bias for exposing for the shadow areas (film dislikes being starved of light), with digital favouring exposure for highlights.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] Latitude is the degree by which one can over, or under expose an image, and still recover an acceptable level of quality from an exposure.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] Typically negative film has a better ability to record a range of brightness than slide/transparency film or digital.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] Digital should be considered to be the reverse of print film, with a good latitude in the shadow range, and a narrow one in the highlight area; in contrast to film's large highlight latitude, and narrow shadow latitude.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] Slide/Transparency film has a narrow latitude in both highlight and shadow areas, requiring greater exposure accuracy.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] Negative film's latitude increases somewhat with high ISO material, in contrast digital tends to narrow on latitude with high ISO settings.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] Areas of a photo where information is lost due to extreme brightness are described as having "blown-out highlights" or "flared highlights".
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] In digital images this information loss is often irreversible, though small problems can be made less noticeable using photo manipulation software.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] Recording to raw image format can correct this problem to some degree, as can using a digital camera with a better sensor.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] Film can often have areas of extreme overexposure but still record detail in those areas.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] This information is usually somewhat recoverable when printing or transferring to digital.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] A loss of highlights in a photograph is usually undesirable, but in some cases can be considered to "enhance" appeal.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] Examples include black and white photography and portraits with an out-of-focus background.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] Areas of a photo where information is lost due to extreme darkness are described as "crushed blacks".
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] Digital capture tends to be more tolerant of underexposure, allowing better recovery of shadow detail, than same-ISO negative print film.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/exposure-photography] Crushed blacks cause loss of detail, but can be used for artistic effect.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/focus-optics] In geometrical optics, a **focus**, also called an **image point**, is a point where light rays originating from a point on an object converge.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/focus-optics] Although the focus is conceptually a point, physically the focus has a spatial extent, called the blur circle.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/focus-optics] This non-ideal focusing may be caused by aberrations of the imaging optics.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/focus-optics] Even in the absence of aberrations, the smallest possible blur circle is the Airy disc caused by diffraction from the optical system's aperture; diffraction is the ultimate limit to the light focusing ability of any optical system.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/focus-optics] Aberrations tend to worsen as the aperture diameter increases, while the Airy circle is smallest for large apertures.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/focus-optics] An image, or image point or region, is **in focus** if light from object points is converged almost as much as possible in the image, and out of focus if light is not well converged.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/focus-optics] The border between these is sometimes defined using a "circle of confusion" criterion.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/focus-optics] Diverging (negative) lenses and convex mirrors do not focus a collimated beam to a point.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/focus-optics] Instead, the focus is the point from which the light appears to be emanating, after it travels through the lens or reflects from the mirror.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/focus-optics] A convex parabolic mirror will reflect a beam of collimated light to make it appear as if it were radiating from the focal point, or conversely, reflect rays directed toward the focus as a collimated beam.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/focus-optics] A convex elliptical mirror will reflect light directed towards one focus as if it were radiating from the other focus, both of which are behind the mirror.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/focus-optics] A convex hyperbolic mirror will reflect rays emanating from the focal point in front of the mirror as if they were emanating from the focal point behind the mirror.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/focus-optics] Conversely, it can focus rays directed at the focal point that is behind the mirror towards the focal point that is in front of the mirror as in a Cassegrain telescope.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] In image processing, a **Gaussian blur** (also known as **Gaussian smoothing**) is the result of blurring an image by a Gaussian function (named after mathematician and scientist Carl Friedrich Gauss).
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] It is a widely used effect in graphics software, typically to reduce image noise and reduce definition.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] The visual effect of this blurring technique is a smooth blur resembling that of viewing the image through a translucent screen, distinctly different from the bokeh effect produced by an out-of-focus lens or the shadow of an object under usual illumination.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] Gaussian smoothing is also used as a pre-processing stage in computer vision algorithms in order to enhance image structures at different scales—see scale space representation and scale space implementation.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] Mathematically, applying a Gaussian blur to an image is the same as convolving the image with a Gaussian function.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] This is also known as a two-dimensional Weierstrass transform.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] By contrast, convolving by a circle (i.e., a circular box blur) would more accurately reproduce the bokeh effect.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] Since the Fourier transform of a Gaussian is another Gaussian, applying a Gaussian blur has the effect of reducing the image's high-frequency components; a Gaussian blur is thus a low-pass filter.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] The Gaussian blur is a type of image-blurring filter that uses a Gaussian function (which also expresses the normal distribution in statistics) for calculating the transformation to apply to each pixel in the image.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] The origin on these axes are at the center (0, 0).
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] When applied in two dimensions, this formula produces a surface whose contours are concentric circles with a Gaussian distribution from the center point.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] Values from this distribution are used to build a convolution matrix which is applied to the original image.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] This convolution process is illustrated visually in the figure on the right.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] Each pixel's new value is set to a weighted average of that pixel's neighborhood.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] The original pixel's value receives the heaviest weight (having the highest Gaussian value) and neighboring pixels receive smaller weights as their distance to the original pixel increases.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] This results in a blur that preserves boundaries and edges better than other, more uniform blurring filters; see also scale space implementation.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] In theory, the Gaussian function at every point on the image will be non-zero, meaning that the entire image would need to be included in the calculations for each pixel.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] In practice, when computing a discrete approximation of the Gaussian function, pixels at a distance of more than 3*σ* have a small enough influence to be considered effectively zero.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] Thus contributions from pixels outside that range can be ignored.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] Typically, an image processing program need only calculate a matrix with dimensions $\lceil 6\sigma \rceil$ × $\lceil 6\sigma \rceil$ (where $\lceil \cdot \rceil$ is the ceiling function) to ensure a result sufficiently close to that obtained by the entire Gaussian distribution.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] In addition to being circularly symmetric, the Gaussian blur can be applied to a two-dimensional image as two independent one-dimensional calculations, and so is termed a separable filter.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] That is, the effect of applying the two-dimensional matrix can also be achieved by applying a series of single-dimensional Gaussian matrices in the horizontal direction, then repeating the process in the vertical direction.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] Applying successive Gaussian blurs to an image has the same effect as applying a single, larger Gaussian blur, whose radius is the square root of the sum of the squares of the blur radii that were actually applied.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] For example, applying successive Gaussian blurs with radii of 6 and 8 gives the same results as applying a single Gaussian blur of radius 10, since ${\sqrt {6^{2}+8^{2}}}=10$ .
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] Because of this relationship, processing time cannot be saved by simulating a Gaussian blur with successive, smaller blurs — the time required will be at least as great as performing the single large blur.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] Gaussian blurring is commonly used when reducing the size of an image.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] When downsampling an image, it is common to apply a low-pass filter to the image prior to resampling.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] This is to ensure that spurious high-frequency information does not appear in the downsampled image (aliasing).
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] Gaussian blurs have nice properties, such as having no sharp edges, and thus do not introduce ringing into the filtered image.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] Gaussian blur is a low-pass filter, attenuating high frequency signals.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] Its amplitude Bode plot (the log scale in the frequency domain) is a parabola.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] This sample matrix is produced by sampling the Gaussian filter kernel (with σ = 0.84089642) at the midpoints of each pixel and then normalizing.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] The center element (at [0, 0]) has the largest value, decreasing symmetrically as distance from the center increases.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] Since the filter kernel's origin is at the center, the matrix starts at ${\textstyle G(-R,-R)}$ and ends at ${\textstyle G(R,R)}$ where R equals the kernel radius.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] The element 0.22508352 (the central one) is 1177 times larger than 0.00019117 which is just outside 3σ.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] A Gaussian blur effect is typically generated by convolving an image with an FIR kernel of Gaussian values.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] In practice, it is best to take advantage of the Gaussian blur’s separable property by dividing the process into two passes.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] In the first pass, a one-dimensional kernel is used to blur the image in only the horizontal or vertical direction.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] In the second pass, the same one-dimensional kernel is used to blur in the remaining direction.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] Discretization is typically achieved by sampling the Gaussian filter kernel at discrete points, normally at positions corresponding to the midpoints of each pixel.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] This reduces the computational cost but, for very small filter kernels, point sampling the Gaussian function with very few samples leads to a large error.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] In these cases, accuracy is maintained (at a slight computational cost) by integration of the Gaussian function over each pixel's area.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] When converting the Gaussian’s continuous values into the discrete values needed for a kernel, the sum of the values will be different from 1.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] This will cause a darkening or brightening of the image.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] To remedy this, the values can be normalized by dividing each term in the kernel by the sum of all terms in the kernel.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] For a more detailed description about the discrete analogue of the Gaussian kernel, see the article on scale-space implementation and.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] The efficiency of FIR breaks down for high sigmas.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] These include the very fast multiple box blurs, the fast and accurate IIR Deriche edge detector, a "stack blur" based on the box blur, and more.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] For processing pre-recorded temporal signals or video, the Gaussian kernel can also be used for smoothing over the temporal domain, since the data are pre-recorded and available in all directions.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] When processing temporal signals or video in real-time situations, the Gaussian kernel cannot, however, be used for temporal smoothing, since it would access data from the future, which obviously cannot be available.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] The time-causal limit kernel corresponds to convolution with an infinite number of truncated exponential kernels coupled in cascade, with specifically chosen time constants.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] For discrete data, this kernel can often be numerically well approximated by a small set of first-order recursive filters coupled in cascade, see for further details.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] Gaussian smoothing is commonly used with edge detection.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] Most edge-detection algorithms are sensitive to noise; the 2-D Laplacian filter, built from a discretization of the Laplace operator, is highly sensitive to noisy environments.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] Using a Gaussian Blur filter before edge detection aims to reduce the level of noise in the image, which improves the result of the following edge-detection algorithm.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] This approach is commonly referred to as Laplacian of Gaussian, or LoG filtering.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] Lower-end digital cameras, including many mobile phone cameras, commonly use gaussian blurring to obscure image noise caused by higher ISO light sensitivities.
[src:depth-of-field-rendering/gaussian-blur] Gaussian blur is automatically applied as part of the image post-processing of the photo by the camera software, leading to an irreversible loss of detail.
